  "prompt": "Is Hinduism monotheistic or polytheistic?",
  "response": "Hinduism is generally considered polytheistic because it involves the worship of multiple deities. These deities include gods and goddesses like Brahma, Vishnu, Shiva, Lakshmi, Saraswati, and many others. Each deity represents different aspects of life and the universe, and they are worshipped in various forms and manifestations.\n\nHowever, Hinduism also has elements of monotheism. Many Hindus believe in a single, supreme reality known as Brahman, which transcends all individual deities and is the ultimate source and essence of everything. Some traditions within Hinduism, such as the worship of Vishnu or Shiva as the supreme deity, can be considered monotheistic in practice.\n\nTherefore, Hinduism can be seen as both polytheistic and monotheistic, depending on the perspective and interpretation within the diverse practices and beliefs of the religion.",
